# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atomic-force-microscopy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Atomic force microscopy (AFM) gathers information by "feeling" or "touching" the surface with a mechanical probe.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Piezoelectric elements that facilitate tiny but accurate and precise movements on (electronic) command enable precise scanning.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Despite the name, the atomic force microscope does not use the nuclear force.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM has three major abilities: force measurement, topographic imaging, and manipulation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In force measurement, AFMs can be used to measure the forces between the probe and the sample as a function of their mutual separation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This can be applied to perform force spectroscopy, to measure the mechanical properties of the sample, such as the sample's Young's modulus, a measure of stiffness.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] For imaging, the reaction of the probe to the forces that the sample imposes on it can be used to form an image of the three-dimensional shape (topography) of a sample surface at a high resolution.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This is achieved by raster scanning the position of the sample with respect to the tip and recording the height of the probe that corresponds to a constant probe-sample interaction .
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The surface topography is commonly displayed as a pseudocolor plot.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] True atomic resolution of the silicon 7×7 surface had to wait a little longer before it was shown by Giessibl.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Subatomic resolution (i.e. the ability to resolve structural details within the electron density of a single atom) has also been achieved by AFM.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In manipulation, the forces between tip and sample can also be used to change the properties of the sample in a controlled way.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Examples of this include atomic manipulation, scanning probe lithography and local stimulation of cells.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Simultaneous with the acquisition of topographical images, other properties of the sample can be measured locally and displayed as an image, often with similarly high resolution.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Examples of such properties are mechanical properties like stiffness or adhesion strength and electrical properties such as conductivity or surface potential.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In fact, the majority of SPM techniques are extensions of AFM that use this modality.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The major difference between atomic force microscopy and competing technologies such as optical microscopy and electron microscopy is that AFM does not use lenses or beam irradiation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Therefore, it does not suffer from a limitation in spatial resolution due to diffraction and aberration, and preparing a space for guiding the beam (by creating a vacuum) and staining the sample are not necessary.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] There are several types of scanning microscopy including SPM (which includes AFM, scanning tunneling microscopy (STM) and near-field scanning optical microscope (SNOM/NSOM), STED microscopy (STED), and scanning electron microscopy and electrochemical AFM, EC-AFM).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Although SNOM and STED use visible, infrared or even terahertz light to illuminate the sample, their resolution is not constrained by the diffraction limit.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] 3 shows an AFM, which typically consists of the following features.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Numbers in parentheses correspond to numbered features in Fig.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Coordinate directions are defined by the coordinate system (0).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The small spring-like cantilever (1) is carried by the support (2).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Optionally, a piezoelectric element (typically made of a ceramic material) (3) oscillates the cantilever (1).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The sharp tip (4) is fixed to the free end of the cantilever (1).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The detector (5) records the deflection and motion of the cantilever (1).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The sample (6) is mounted on the sample stage (8).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An xyz drive (7) permits to displace the sample (6) and the sample stage (8) in x, y, and z directions with respect to the tip apex (4).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] 3 shows the drive attached to the sample, the drive can also be attached to the tip, or independent drives can be attached to both, since it is the relative displacement of the sample and tip that needs to be controlled.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Controllers and plotter are not shown in Fig.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] According to the configuration described above, the interaction between tip and sample, which can be an atomic-scale phenomenon, is transduced into changes of the motion of cantilever, which is a macro-scale phenomenon.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The detector (5) of AFM measures the deflection (displacement with respect to the equilibrium position) of the cantilever and converts it into an electrical signal.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The intensity of this signal will be proportional to the displacement of the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Various methods of detection can be used, e.g. interferometry, optical levers, the piezoelectric method, and STM-based detectors (see section "AFM cantilever deflection measurement").
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When using the AFM to image a sample, the tip is brought into contact with the sample, and the sample is raster scanned along an x–y grid.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Most commonly, an electronic feedback loop is employed to keep the probe-sample force constant during scanning.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This feedback loop has the cantilever deflection as input, and its output controls the distance along the z axis between the probe support (2 in fig.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As long as the tip remains in contact with the sample, and the sample is scanned in the x–y plane, height variations in the sample will change the deflection of the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The feedback then adjusts the height of the probe support so that the deflection is restored to a user-defined value (the setpoint).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A properly adjusted feedback loop adjusts the support-sample separation continuously during the scanning motion, such that the deflection remains approximately constant.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In this situation, the feedback output equals the sample surface topography to within a small error.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Historically, a different operation method has been used, in which the sample-probe support distance is kept constant and not controlled by a feedback (servo mechanism).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In this mode, usually referred to as "constant-height mode", the deflection of the cantilever is recorded as a function of the sample x–y position.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As long as the tip is in contact with the sample, the deflection then corresponds to surface topography.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This method is now less commonly used because the forces between tip and sample are not controlled, which can lead to forces high enough to damage the tip or the sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] It is, however, common practice to record the deflection even when scanning in constant force mode, with feedback.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This reveals the small tracking error of the feedback, and can sometimes reveal features that the feedback was not able to adjust for.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM signals, such as sample height or cantilever deflection, are recorded on a computer during the x–y scan.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] They are plotted in a pseudocolor image, in which each pixel represents an x–y position on the sample, and the color represents the recorded signal.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM was invented by IBM scientists in 1985.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The precursor to the AFM, the scanning tunneling microscope (STM), was developed by Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer in the early 1980s at IBM Research – Zurich, a development that earned them the 1986 Nobel Prize for Physics.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Binnig invented the atomic force microscope and the first experimental implementation was made by Binnig, Quate and Gerber in 1986.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The first commercially available atomic force microscope was introduced in 1989.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM is one of the foremost tools for imaging, measuring, and manipulating matter at the nanoscale.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM has been applied to problems in a wide range of disciplines of the natural sciences, including solid-state physics, semiconductor science and technology, molecular engineering, polymer chemistry and physics, surface chemistry, molecular biology, cell biology, and medicine.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In molecular biology, AFM can be used to study the structure and mechanical properties of protein complexes and assemblies.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] For example, AFM has been used to image microtubules and measure their stiffness.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In cellular biology, AFM can be used to attempt to distinguish cancer cells and normal cells based on a hardness of cells, and to evaluate interactions between a specific cell and its neighboring cells in a competitive culture system.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM can also be used to indent cells, to study how they regulate the stiffness or shape of the cell membrane or wall.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In some variations, electric potentials can also be scanned using conducting cantilevers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In more advanced versions, currents can be passed through the tip to probe the electrical conductivity or transport of the underlying surface, but this is a challenging task with few research groups reporting consistent data (as of 2004).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM techniques such as conductive atomic force microscopy (C-AFM) and Kelvin probe force microscopy (KPFM) are increasingly used in solid-state battery research to analyze local conductivity variations, interfacial potential changes, and degradation mechanisms at the nanoscale.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Electron micrograph of a used AFM cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM consists of a cantilever with a sharp tip (probe) at its end that is used to scan the specimen surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The cantilever is typically silicon or silicon nitride with a tip radius of curvature on the order of nanometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When the tip is brought into proximity of a sample surface, forces between the tip and the sample lead to a deflection of the cantilever according to Hooke's law.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Depending on the situation, forces that are measured in AFM include mechanical contact force, van der Waals forces, capillary forces, chemical bonding, electrostatic forces, magnetic forces (see magnetic force microscope, MFM), Casimir forces, solvation forces, etc.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Along with force, additional quantities may simultaneously be measured through the use of specialized types of probes (see scanning thermal microscopy, scanning joule expansion microscopy, photothermal microspectroscopy, etc.).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM can be operated in a number of modes, depending on the application.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In general, possible imaging modes are divided into static (also called *contact*) modes and a variety of dynamic (non-contact or "tapping") modes where the cantilever is vibrated or oscillated at a given frequency.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Despite the nomenclature, repulsive contact can occur or be avoided both in amplitude modulation AFM and frequency modulation AFM, depending on the settings.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In contact mode, the tip is "dragged" across the surface of the sample and the contours of the surface are measured either using the deflection of the cantilever directly or, more commonly, using the feedback signal required to keep the cantilever at a constant position.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Because the measurement of a static signal is prone to noise and drift, low stiffness cantilevers (i.e. cantilevers with a low spring constant, k) are used to achieve a large enough deflection signal while keeping the interaction force low.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Close to the surface of the sample, attractive forces can be quite strong, causing the tip to "snap-in" to the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Thus, contact mode AFM is almost always done at a depth where the overall force is repulsive, that is, in firm "contact" with the solid surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In ambient conditions, most samples develop a liquid meniscus layer.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Because of this, keeping the probe tip close enough to the sample for short-range forces to become detectable while preventing the tip from sticking to the surface presents a major problem for contact mode in ambient conditions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Dynamic contact mode (also called intermittent contact, AC mode or tapping mode) was developed to bypass this problem.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Nowadays, tapping mode is the most frequently used AFM mode when operating in ambient conditions or in liquids.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In *tapping mode*, the cantilever is driven to oscillate up and down at or near its resonance frequency.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This oscillation is commonly achieved with a small piezo element in the cantilever holder, but other possibilities include an AC magnetic field (with magnetic cantilevers), piezoelectric cantilevers, or periodic heating with a modulated laser beam.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The amplitude of this oscillation usually varies from several nm to 200 nm.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In tapping mode, the frequency and amplitude of the driving signal are kept constant, leading to a constant amplitude of the cantilever oscillation as long as there is no drift or interaction with the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The interaction of forces acting on the cantilever when the tip comes close to the surface, van der Waals forces, dipole–dipole interactions, electrostatic forces, etc. cause the amplitude of the cantilever's oscillation to change (usually decrease) as the tip gets closer to the sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This amplitude is used as the parameter that goes into the electronic servo that controls the height of the cantilever above the sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The servo adjusts the height to maintain a set cantilever oscillation amplitude as the cantilever is scanned over the sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A *tapping AFM* image is therefore produced by imaging the force of the intermittent contacts of the tip with the sample surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Although the peak forces applied during the contacting part of the oscillation can be much higher than typically used in contact mode, tapping mode generally lessens the damage done to the surface and the tip compared to the amount done in contact mode.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This can be explained by the short duration of the applied force, and because the lateral forces between tip and sample are significantly lower in tapping mode over contact mode.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Tapping mode imaging is gentle enough even for the visualization of supported lipid bilayers or adsorbed single polymer molecules (for instance, 0.4 nm thick chains of synthetic polyelectrolytes) under liquid medium.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] With proper scanning parameters, the conformation of single molecules can remain unchanged for hours, and even single molecular motors can be imaged while moving.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When operating in tapping mode, the phase of the cantilever's oscillation with respect to the driving signal can be recorded as well.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This signal channel contains information about the energy dissipated by the cantilever in each oscillation cycle.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Samples that contain regions of varying stiffness or with different adhesion properties can give a contrast in this channel that is not visible in the topographic image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Extracting the sample's material properties in a quantitative manner from phase images, however, is often not feasible.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In non-contact atomic force microscopy mode, the tip of the cantilever does not contact the sample surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The cantilever is instead oscillated at either its resonant frequency (frequency modulation) or just above (amplitude modulation) where the amplitude of oscillation is typically a few nanometers (<10 nm) down to a few picometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The van der Waals forces, which are strongest from 1 nm to 10 nm above the surface, or any other long-range force that extends above the surface acts to decrease the resonance frequency of the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This decrease in resonant frequency combined with the feedback loop system maintains a constant oscillation amplitude or frequency by adjusting the average tip-to-sample distance.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Measuring the tip-to-sample distance at each (x,y) data point allows the scanning software to construct a topographic image of the sample surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Non-contact mode AFM does not suffer from tip or sample degradation effects that are sometimes observed after taking numerous scans with contact AFM.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This makes non-contact AFM preferable to contact AFM for measuring soft samples, e.g. biological samples and organic thin film.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In the case of rigid samples, contact and non-contact images may look the same.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] However, if a few monolayers of adsorbed fluid are lying on the surface of a rigid sample, the images may look quite different.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An AFM operating in contact mode will penetrate the liquid layer to image the underlying surface, whereas in non-contact mode an AFM will oscillate above the adsorbed fluid layer to image both the liquid and surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Schemes for dynamic mode operation include frequency modulation where a phase-locked loop is used to track the cantilever's resonance frequency and the more common amplitude modulation with a servo loop in place to keep the cantilever excitation to a defined amplitude.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In frequency modulation, changes in the oscillation frequency provide information about tip-sample interactions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Frequency can be measured with very high sensitivity and thus the frequency modulation mode allows for the use of very stiff cantilevers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Stiff cantilevers provide stability very close to the surface and, as a result, this technique was the first AFM technique to provide true atomic resolution in ultra-high vacuum conditions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In amplitude modulation, changes in the oscillation amplitude or phase provide the feedback signal for imaging.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In amplitude modulation, changes in the phase of oscillation can be used to discriminate between different types of materials on the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Amplitude modulation can be operated either in the non-contact or in the intermittent contact regime.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In dynamic contact mode, the cantilever is oscillated such that the separation distance between the cantilever tip and the sample surface is modulated.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Amplitude modulation has also been used in the non-contact regime to image with atomic resolution by using very stiff cantilevers and small amplitudes in an ultra-high vacuum environment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Image formation is a plotting method that produces a color mapping through changing the x–y position of the tip while scanning and recording the measured variable, i.e. the intensity of control signal, to each x–y coordinate.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The color mapping shows the measured value corresponding to each coordinate.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The image expresses the intensity of a value as a hue.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Usually, the correspondence between the intensity of a value and a hue is shown as a color scale in the explanatory notes accompanying the image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Operation mode of image forming of the AFM are generally classified into two groups from the viewpoint of whether or not it uses z-Feedback loop (not shown) to maintain the tip-sample distance to keep signal intensity exported by the detector.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The first one (using z-Feedback loop), said to be "constant **XX** mode" (**XX** is something which kept by z-Feedback loop).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When the distance between the probe and the sample is brought to the range where atomic force may be detected, while a cantilever is excited in its natural eigenfrequency (*f*0), the resonance frequency *f* of the cantilever may shift from its original resonance frequency.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In other words, in the range where atomic force may be detected, a frequency shift (*df* =*f*–*f*0) will also be observed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When the distance between the probe and the sample is in the **non-contact** region, the frequency shift increases in negative direction as the distance between the probe and the sample gets smaller.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When the sample has concavity and convexity, the distance between the tip-apex and the sample varies in accordance with the concavity and convexity accompanied with a scan of the sample along x–y direction (without height regulation in z-direction).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As a result, the frequency shift arises.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The image in which the values of the frequency obtained by a raster scan along the x–y direction of the sample surface are plotted against the x–y coordination of each measurement point is called a constant-height image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] On the other hand, the df may be kept constant by moving the probe upward and downward (See (3) of FIG.5) in z-direction using a negative feedback (by using z-feedback loop) while the raster scan of the sample surface along the x–y direction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The image in which the amounts of the negative feedback (the moving distance of the probe upward and downward in z-direction) are plotted against the x–y coordination of each measurement point is a topographic image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In other words, the topographic image is a trace of the tip of the probe regulated so that the df is constant and it may also be considered to be a plot of a constant-height surface of the df.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Besides imaging, AFM can be used for force spectroscopy, the direct measurement of tip-sample interaction forces as a function of the gap between the tip and sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The result of this measurement is called a force-distance curve.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] For this method, the AFM tip is extended towards and retracted from the surface as the deflection of the cantilever is monitored as a function of piezoelectric displacement.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] These measurements have been used to measure nanoscale contacts, atomic bonding, Van der Waals forces, and Casimir forces, dissolution forces in liquids and single molecule stretching and rupture forces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM has also been used to measure, in an aqueous environment, the dispersion force due to polymer adsorbed on the substrate.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Forces of the order of a few piconewtons can now be routinely measured with a vertical distance resolution of better than 0.1 nanometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Force spectroscopy can be performed with either static or dynamic modes.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In dynamic modes, information about the cantilever vibration is monitored in addition to the static deflection.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Problems with the technique include no direct measurement of the tip-sample separation and the common need for low-stiffness cantilevers, which tend to "snap" to the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An AFM that directly measures the tip-sample separation has been developed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The snap-in can be reduced by measuring in liquids or by using stiffer cantilevers, but in the latter case a more sensitive deflection sensor is needed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] By applying a small dither to the tip, the stiffness (force gradient) of the bond can be measured as well.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Force spectroscopy is used in biophysics to measure the mechanical properties of living material (such as tissue or cells) or detect structures of different stiffness buried into the bulk of the sample using the stiffness tomography.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Another application was to measure the interaction forces between from one hand a material stuck on the tip of the cantilever, and from another hand the surface of particles either free or occupied by the same material.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] From the adhesion force distribution curve, a mean value of the forces has been derived.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] It allowed to make a cartography of the surface of the particles, covered or not by the material.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM has also been used for mechanically unfolding proteins.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In such experiments, the analyzes of the mean unfolding forces with the appropriate model leads to the obtainment of the information about the unfolding rate and free energy profile parameters of the protein.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM can be used to image atoms and structures on a variety of surfaces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The atom at the apex of the tip "senses" individual atoms on the underlying surface when it begins the formation of chemical bonds with each atom.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Because these chemical interactions subtly alter the tip's vibration frequency, they can be detected and mapped.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This principle was used to distinguish between atoms of silicon, tin and lead on an alloy surface, by comparing these atomic fingerprints with values obtained from density functional theory (DFT) simulations.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Interaction forces must be measured precisely for each type of atom expected in the sample, and then to compare with forces given by DFT simulations.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] It was found that the tip interacted most strongly with silicon atoms, and interacted 24% and 41% less strongly with tin and lead atoms, respectively.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Each different type of atom could be identified in the matrix as the tip using this information.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An AFM probe has a sharp tip on the free-swinging end of a cantilever that protrudes from a holder.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The dimensions of the cantilever are in the scale of micrometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The radius of the tip is usually on the scale of a few nanometers to a few tens of nanometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This device is most commonly called an "AFM probe", but other names include "AFM tip" and "cantilever" (employing the name of a single part as the name of the whole device).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An AFM probe is a particular type of SPM probe.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM probes are manufactured with MEMS technology.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Most AFM probes used are made from silicon (Si), but borosilicate glass and silicon nitride are also in use.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM probes are considered consumables as they are often replaced when the tip apex becomes dull or contaminated or when the cantilever is broken.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] They can cost from a couple of tens of dollars up to hundreds of dollars per cantilever for the most specialized cantilever/probe combinations.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] To use the device, the tip is brought very close to the surface of the object under investigation, and the cantilever is deflected by the interaction between the tip and the surface, which is what the AFM is designed to measure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A spatial map of the interaction can be made by measuring the deflection at many points on a 2D surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Several types of interaction can be detected.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Depending on the interaction under investigation, the surface of the tip of the AFM probe needs to be modified with a coating.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Among the coatings used are gold – for covalent bonding of biological molecules and the detection of their interaction with a surface, diamond for increased wear resistance and magnetic coatings for detecting the magnetic properties of the investigated surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Another solution exists to achieve high resolution magnetic imaging: equipping the probe with a microSQUID.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The AFM tips are fabricated using silicon micro machining and the precise positioning of the microSQUID loop is achieved using electron beam lithography.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The additional attachment of a quantum dot to the tip apex of a conductive probe enables surface potential imaging with high lateral resolution, scanning quantum dot microscopy.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The surface of the cantilevers can also be modified.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] These coatings are mostly applied in order to increase the reflectance of the cantilever and to improve the deflection signal.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The forces between the tip and the sample strongly depend on the geometry of the tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Various studies were exploited in the past years to write the forces as a function of the tip parameters.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Among the different forces between the tip and the sample, the water meniscus forces are highly interesting, both in air and liquid environment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Other forces must be considered, like the Coulomb force, van der Waals forces, double layer interactions, solvation forces, hydration and hydrophobic forces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Water meniscus forces are highly interesting for AFM measurements in air.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Due to the ambient humidity, a thin layer of water is formed between the tip and the sample during air measurements.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The resulting capillary force gives rise to a strong attractive force that pulls the tip onto the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In fact, the adhesion force measured between tip and sample in ambient air of finite humidity is usually dominated by capillary forces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As a consequence, it is difficult to pull the tip away from the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] For soft samples including many polymers and in particular biological materials, the strong adhesive capillary force gives rise to sample degradation and destruction upon imaging in contact mode.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Historically, these problems were an important motivation for the development of dynamic imaging in air (e.g.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] During tapping mode imaging in air, capillary bridges still form.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Yet, for suitable imaging conditions, the capillary bridges are formed and broken in every oscillation cycle of the cantilever normal to the surface, as can be inferred from an analysis of cantilever amplitude and phase vs. distance curves.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As a consequence, destructive shear forces are largely reduced and soft samples can be investigated.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] where *γ*L, is the surface energy and *r*0 and *r*1 are defined in the figure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] where *θ* is the angle between the tip's surface and the liquid's surface while *h* is the height difference between the surrounding liquid and the top of the miniscus.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The same formula could also be calculated as a function of relative humidity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Gao calculated formulas for different tip geometries.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As an example, the force decreases by 20% for a conical tip with respect to a spherical tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] When these forces are calculated, a difference must be made between the wet on dry situation and the wet on wet situation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] where *δ* is the half cone angle and *r*0 and *h* are parameters of the meniscus profile.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The most common method for cantilever-deflection measurements is the beam-deflection method.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In this method, laser light from a solid-state diode is reflected off the back of the cantilever and collected by a position-sensitive detector (PSD) consisting of two closely spaced photodiodes, whose output signal is collected by a differential amplifier.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Angular displacement of the cantilever results in one photodiode collecting more light than the other photodiode, producing an output signal (the difference between the photodiode signals normalized by their sum), which is proportional to the deflection of the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The sensitivity of the beam-deflection method is very high, and a noise floor on the order of 10 fm Hz−1⁄2 can be obtained routinely in a well-designed system.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Although this method is sometimes called the "optical lever" method, the signal is not amplified if the beam path is made longer.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A longer beam path increases the motion of the reflected spot on the photodiodes, but also widens the spot by the same amount due to diffraction, so that the same amount of optical power is moved from one photodiode to the other.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The "optical leverage" (output signal of the detector divided by deflection of the cantilever) is inversely proportional to the numerical aperture of the beam focusing optics, as long as the focused laser spot is small enough to fall completely on the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] It is also inversely proportional to the length of the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The relative popularity of the beam-deflection method can be explained by its high sensitivity and simple operation, and by the fact that cantilevers do not require electrical contacts or other special treatments, and can therefore be fabricated relatively cheaply with sharp integrated tips.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Many other methods for beam-deflection measurements exist.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM scanners are made from piezoelectric material, which expands and contracts proportionally to an applied voltage.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Whether they elongate or contract depends upon the polarity of the voltage applied.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Traditionally the tip or sample is mounted on a "tripod" of three piezo crystals, with each responsible for scanning in the *x*,*y* and *z* directions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In 1986, the same year as the AFM was invented, a new piezoelectric scanner, the tube scanner, was developed for use in STM.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Later tube scanners were incorporated into AFMs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The tube scanner can move the sample in the *x*, *y*, and *z* directions using a single tube piezo with a single interior contact and four external contacts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] An advantage of the tube scanner compared to the original tripod design, is better vibrational isolation, resulting from the higher resonant frequency of the single element construction, in combination with a low resonant frequency isolation stage.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A disadvantage is that the *x*-*y* motion can cause unwanted *z* motion resulting in distortion.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Another popular design for AFM scanners is the flexure stage, which uses separate piezos for each axis, and couples them through a flexure mechanism.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Scanners are characterized by their sensitivity, which is the ratio of piezo movement to piezo voltage, i.e., by how much the piezo material extends or contracts per applied volt.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Due to the differences in material or size, the sensitivity varies from scanner to scanner.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Sensitivity varies non-linearly with respect to scan size.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Piezo scanners exhibit more sensitivity at the end than at the beginning of a scan.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This causes the forward and reverse scans to behave differently and display hysteresis between the two scan directions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This can be corrected by applying a non-linear voltage to the piezo electrodes to cause linear scanner movement and calibrating the scanner accordingly.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] One disadvantage of this approach is that it requires re-calibration because the precise non-linear voltage needed to correct non-linear movement will change as the piezo ages (see below).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This problem can be circumvented by adding a linear sensor to the sample stage or piezo stage to detect the true movement of the piezo.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Deviations from ideal movement can be detected by the sensor and corrections applied to the piezo drive signal to correct for non-linear piezo movement.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This design is known as a "closed loop" AFM.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Non-sensored piezo AFMs are referred to as "open loop" AFMs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The sensitivity of piezoelectric materials decreases exponentially with time.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This causes most of the change in sensitivity to occur in the initial stages of the scanner's life.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Piezoelectric scanners are run for approximately 48 hours before they are shipped from the factory so that they are past the point where they may have large changes in sensitivity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As the scanner ages, the sensitivity will change less with time and the scanner would seldom require recalibration, though various manufacturer manuals recommend monthly to semi-monthly calibration of open loop AFMs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM has several advantages over the scanning electron microscope (SEM).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Unlike the electron microscope, which provides a two-dimensional projection or a two-dimensional image of a sample, the AFM provides a three-dimensional surface profile.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In addition, samples viewed by AFM do not require any special treatments (such as metal/carbon coatings) that would irreversibly change or damage the sample, and does not typically suffer from charging artifacts in the final image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] While an electron microscope needs an expensive vacuum environment for proper operation, most AFM modes can work perfectly well in ambient air or even a liquid environment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] This makes it possible to study biological macromolecules and even living organisms.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In principle, AFM can provide higher resolution than SEM.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] It has been shown to give true atomic resolution in ultra-high vacuum (UHV) and, more recently, in liquid environments.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] High resolution AFM is comparable in resolution to scanning tunneling microscopy and transmission electron microscopy.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM can also be combined with a variety of optical microscopy and spectroscopy techniques such as fluorescent microscopy of infrared spectroscopy, giving rise to scanning near-field optical microscopy, nano-FTIR and further expanding its applicability.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Combined AFM-optical instruments have been applied primarily in the biological sciences but have recently attracted strong interest in photovoltaics and energy-storage research, polymer sciences, nanotechnology and even medical research.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] A disadvantage of AFM compared with the scanning electron microscope (SEM) is the single scan image size.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] In one pass, the SEM can image an area on the order of square millimeters with a depth of field on the order of millimeters, whereas the AFM can only image a maximum scanning area of about 150×150 micrometers and a maximum height on the order of 10–20 micrometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] One method of improving the scanned area size for AFM is by using parallel probes in a fashion similar to that of millipede data storage.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The scanning speed of an AFM is also a limitation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Traditionally, an AFM cannot scan images as fast as an SEM, requiring several minutes for a typical scan, while an SEM is capable of scanning at near real-time, although at relatively low quality.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The relatively slow rate of scanning during AFM imaging often leads to thermal drift in the image making the AFM less suited for measuring accurate distances between topographical features on the image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] However, several fast-acting designs were suggested to increase microscope scanning productivity including what is being termed videoAFM (reasonable quality images are being obtained with videoAFM at video rate: faster than the average SEM).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] To eliminate image distortions induced by thermal drift, several methods have been introduced.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] AFM images can also be affected by nonlinearity, hysteresis, and creep of the piezoelectric material and cross-talk between the *x*, *y*, *z* axes that may require software enhancement and filtering.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Such filtering could "flatten" out real topographical features.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] However, newer AFMs utilize real-time correction software (for example, feature-oriented scanning) or closed-loop scanners, which practically eliminate these problems.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Some AFMs also use separated orthogonal scanners (as opposed to a single tube), which also serve to eliminate part of the cross-talk problems.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] As with any other imaging technique, there is the possibility of image artifacts, which could be induced by an unsuitable tip, a poor operating environment, or even by the sample itself, as depicted on the right.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] These image artifacts are unavoidable; however, their occurrence and effect on results can be reduced through various methods.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Artifacts resulting from a too-coarse tip can be caused for example by inappropriate handling or de facto collisions with the sample by either scanning too fast or having an unreasonably rough surface, causing actual wearing of the tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Due to the nature of AFM probes, they cannot normally measure steep walls or overhangs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Specially made cantilevers and AFMs can be used to modulate the probe sideways as well as up and down (as with dynamic contact and non-contact modes) to measure sidewalls, at the cost of more expensive cantilevers, lower lateral resolution and additional artifacts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] The latest efforts in integrating nanotechnology and biological research have been successful and show much promise for the future, including in fields such as nanobiomechanics.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Since nanoparticles are a potential vehicle of drug delivery, the biological responses of cells to these nanoparticles are continuously being explored to optimize their efficacy and how their design could be improved.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Pyrgiotakis et al. were able to study the interaction between CeO2 and Fe2O3 engineered nanoparticles and cells by attaching the engineered nanoparticles to the AFM tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Studies have taken advantage of AFM to obtain further information on the behavior of live cells in biological media.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Real-time atomic force spectroscopy (or nanoscopy) and dynamic atomic force spectroscopy have been used to study live cells and membrane proteins and their dynamic behavior at high resolution, on the nanoscale.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Imaging and obtaining information on the topography and the properties of the cells has also given insight into chemical processes and mechanisms that occur through cell-cell interaction and interactions with other signaling molecules (ex. ligands).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Evans and Calderwood used single cell force microscopy to study cell adhesion forces, bond kinetics/dynamic bond strength and its role in chemical processes such as cell signaling.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/atomic-force-microscopy] Scheuring, Lévy, and Rigaud reviewed studies in which AFM to explore the crystal structure of membrane proteins of photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A **cantilever** is a structural element that is firmly attached to a fixed structure at one end and is unsupported at the other end.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Sometimes it projects from a vertical surface such as a wall.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A cantilever can be in the form of a beam, plate, truss, or slab.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] When subjected to a structural load at its far, unsupported end, the cantilever carries the load to the support where it applies a shear stress and a bending moment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Cantilever construction allows overhanging structures without external support.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Cantilevers are widely found in construction, notably in cantilever bridges and balconies (see corbel).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In cantilever bridges, the cantilevers are usually built as pairs, with each cantilever used to support one end of a central section.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The Forth Bridge in Scotland is an example of a cantilever truss bridge.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A cantilever in a traditionally timber framed building is called a jetty or forebay.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In the southern United States, a historic barn type is the cantilever barn of log construction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Temporary cantilevers are often used in construction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The partially constructed structure creates a cantilever, but the completed structure does not act as a cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] This is very helpful when temporary supports, or falsework, cannot be used to support the structure while it is being built (e.g., over a busy roadway or river, or in a deep valley).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Therefore, some truss arch bridges (see Navajo Bridge) are built from each side as cantilevers until the spans reach each other and are then jacked apart to stress them in compression before finally joining.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Nearly all cable-stayed bridges are built using cantilevers as this is one of their chief advantages.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Many box girder bridges are built segmentally, or in short pieces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] This type of construction lends itself well to balanced cantilever construction where the bridge is built in both directions from a single support.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] These structures rely heavily on torque and rotational equilibrium for their stability.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In an architectural application, Frank Lloyd Wright's Fallingwater used cantilevers to project large balconies.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The East Stand at Elland Road Stadium in Leeds was, when completed, the largest cantilever stand in the world holding 17,000 spectators.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The roof built over the stands at Old Trafford uses a cantilever so that no supports will block views of the field.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The old (now demolished) Miami Stadium had a similar roof over the spectator area.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The largest cantilevered roof in Europe is located at St James' Park in Newcastle-Upon-Tyne, the home stadium of Newcastle United F.C.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Less obvious examples of cantilevers are free-standing (vertical) radio towers without guy-wires, and chimneys, which resist being blown over by the wind through cantilever action at their base.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The cantilever is commonly used in the wings of fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Early aircraft had light structures braced with wires and struts which introduced aerodynamic drag and limited performance.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] While heavier, the cantilever avoids this issue and allows the plane to fly faster.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Hugo Junkers pioneered the cantilever wing in 1915.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Only a dozen years after the Wright Brothers' initial flights, Junkers endeavored to eliminate virtually all major external bracing members to decrease airframe drag.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The result was the Junkers J 1 pioneering all-metal monoplane of late 1915, designed with all-metal cantilever wing panels.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] About a year after the initial success of the Junkers J 1, Reinhold Platz of Fokker also achieved success with a cantilever-winged sesquiplane built instead with wooden materials, the Fokker V.1.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In the cantilever wing, one or more strong *spars* run along the span of the wing.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The end fixed rigidly to the central fuselage is known as the root and the far end as the tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The wings generate lift which the spars carry through to the fuselage.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] To resist horizontal shear from drag or engine thrust, the wing must also form a stiff cantilever in the horizontal plane.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A single-spar design will usually be fitted with a second, smaller, drag-spar nearer the trailing edge, braced to the main spar via internal members or a stressed skin.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The wing must also resist twisting forces, achieved by cross-bracing or otherwise stiffening the main structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Cantilever wings require much stronger and heavier spars than would be needed in a wire-braced design.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] However, as aircraft speed increases, the drag of the bracing increases sharply, while the wing structure must be strengthened, typically by increasing the strength of the spars and the thickness of the skinning.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] At speeds of around 200 miles per hour (320 km/h) the drag of the bracing becomes excessive and the wing strong enough to be made a cantilever without weight penalty.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Increases in engine power through the late 1920s and early 1930s raised speeds through this zone and by the late 1930s cantilever wings had almost wholly superseded braced ones.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Other changes including enclosed cockpits, retractable undercarriage, landing flaps and stressed-skin construction furthered the design revolution, with the pivotal moment acknowledged to be the MacRobertson England-Australia air race of 1934, won by a de Havilland DH.88 Comet.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Cantilever wings are now almost universal with bracing only being used for some slower aircraft where lighter weight is prioritized over speed, such as in the ultralight class.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Cantilevered beams are the most ubiquitous structures in the field of microelectromechanical systems (MEMS).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] An early example of a MEMS cantilever is the Resonistor, an electromechanical monolithic resonator.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] MEMS cantilevers are commonly fabricated from silicon (Si), silicon nitride (Si3N4), or polymers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] The fabrication process typically involves undercutting the cantilever structure to *release* it, often with an anisotropic wet or dry etching technique.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Without cantilever transducers, atomic force microscopy would not be possible.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A large number of research groups are attempting to develop cantilever arrays as biosensors for medical diagnostic applications.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] MEMS cantilevers are also finding application as radio frequency filters and resonators.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Types of MEMS cantilevers include unimorphs and bimorphs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Challenges for their practical application lie in the square and cubic dependences of cantilever performance specifications on dimensions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] These superlinear dependences mean that cantilevers are quite sensitive to variation in process parameters, particularly the thickness as this is generally difficult to accurately measure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] However, it has been shown that microcantilever thicknesses can be precisely measured and that this variation can be quantified.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Controlling residual stress can also be difficult.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] A microcantilever may be used as chemical sensor by coating it with a material that binds to specific chemicals.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] For example, an immunosensor based on an antibody layer that interacts selectively with a particular immunogen.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In the static mode of operation, the sensor response is represented by the beam bending with respect to a reference microcantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Alternatively, microcantilever sensors can be operated in the dynamic mode.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] In this case, the beam vibrates at its resonance frequency and a variation in this parameter indicates the concentration of the analyte.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] Porous microcantilevers have been fabricated providing a much larger surface area for analyte to bind to.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/cantilever] This improves sensitivity by raising the ratio of the analyte mass to the cantilever mass.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Techniques that can be used to perform force spectroscopy include atomic force microscopy, optical tweezers, magnetic tweezers, acoustic force spectroscopy, microneedles, and biomembranes.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Force spectroscopy measures the behavior of a molecule under stretching or torsional mechanical force.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] As a single-molecule technique, as opposed to typical ensemble spectroscopies, it allows a researcher to determine properties of the particular molecule under study.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In particular, rare events such as conformational change, which are masked in an ensemble, may be observed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] There are many ways to accurately manipulate single molecules.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Prominent among these are optical or magnetic tweezers, atomic-force-microscope (AFM) cantilevers and acoustic force spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In all of these techniques, a biomolecule, such as protein or DNA, or some other biopolymer has one end bound to a surface or micrometre-sized bead and the other to a force sensor.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The force sensor is usually a micrometre-sized bead or a cantilever, whose displacement can be measured to determine the force.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Molecules adsorbed on a surface are picked up by a microscopic tip (nanometres wide) that is located on the end of an elastic cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In a more sophisticated version of this experiment (Chemical Force Microscopy) the tips are covalently functionalized with the molecules of interest.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] A piezoelectric controller then pulls up the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] If some force is acting on the elastic cantilever (for example because some molecule is being stretched between the surface and the tip), this will deflect upward (repulsive force) or downward (attractive force).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] According to Hooke's law, this deflection will be proportional to the force acting on the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Deflection is measured by the position of a laser beam reflected by the cantilever.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] This kind of set-up can measure forces as low as 10 pN (10−11 N), the fundamental resolution limit is given by the cantilever's thermal noise.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The so-called force curve is the graph of force (or more precisely, of cantilever deflection) versus the piezoelectric position on the Z axis.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] An ideal Hookean spring, for example, would display a straight diagonal force curve.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Typically, the force curves observed in the force spectroscopy experiments consist of a contact (diagonal) region where the probe contacts the sample surface, and a non-contact region where the probe is off the sample surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] When the restoring force of the cantilever exceeds tip-sample adhesion force the probe jumps out of contact, and the magnitude of this jump is often used as a measure of adhesion force or rupture force.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In general the rupture of a tip-surface bond is a stochastic process; therefore reliable quantification of the adhesion force requires taking multiple individual force curves.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The histogram of the adhesion forces obtained in these multiple measurements provides the main data output for force spectroscopy measurement.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In biophysics, single-molecule force spectroscopy can be used to study the energy landscape underlying the interaction between two bio-molecules, like proteins.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Here, one binding partner can be attached to a cantilever tip via a flexible linker molecule (PEG chain), while the other one is immobilized on a substrate surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In a typical approach, the cantilever is repeatedly approached and retracted from the sample at a constant speed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In some cases, binding between the two partners will occur, which will become visible in the force curve, as the use of a flexible linker gives rise to a characteristic curve shape (see Worm-like chain model) distinct from adhesion.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The collected rupture forces can then be analysed as a function of the bond loading rate.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The resulting graph of the average rupture force as a function of the loading rate is called the *force spectrum* and forms the basic dataset for *dynamic force spectroscopy*.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In the ideal case of a single sharp energy barrier for the tip-sample interactions the dynamic force spectrum will show a linear increase of the rupture force as function of a logarithm of the loading rate, as described by a model proposed by Bell et al.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Here, the slope of the rupture force spectrum is equal to the ${\frac {k_{B}T}{x_{\beta }}}$ , where $x_{\beta }$ is the distance from the energy minimum to the transition state.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] So far, a number of theoretical models exist describing the relationship between loading rate and rupture force, based upon different assumptions and predicting distinct curve shapes.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] For example, Ma X.,Gosai A. et al., utilized dynamic force spectroscopy along with molecular dynamics simulations to find out the binding force between thrombin, a blood coagulation protein, and its DNA aptamer.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] A recently developed technique, acoustic force spectroscopy (AFS), allows the force manipulation of hundreds of single-molecules and single-cells in parallel, providing high experimental throughput.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In this technique, a piezo element resonantly excites planar acoustic waves over a microfluidic chip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The generated acoustic waves are capable of exerting forces on microspheres with different density than the surrounding medium.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Biomolecules, such as DNA, RNA or proteins, can be individually tethered between the microspheres and a surface and then probed by the acoustic forces exerted by the piezo sensor.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] With AFS devices it is possible to apply forces ranging from 0 to several hundreds of picoNewtons on hundreds of microspheres and obtain force-extension curves or histograms of rupture forces of many individual events in parallel.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] This technique is mostly utilized to study DNA-bindings protein.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] For example, AFS was used to examine bacterial transcription with presence of antibacterial agents.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Viral proteins also can be studied by AFS, for instance this technique was used to explore DNA compaction along with other single-molecule approaches.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Cells also can be manipulated by the acoustic forces directly, or by using microspheres as handles.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Another technique that has been gaining ground for single molecule experiments is the use of optical tweezers for applying mechanical forces on molecules.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] A strongly focused laser beam has the ability to catch and hold particles (of dielectric material) in a size range from nanometers to micrometers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The trapping action of optical tweezers results from the dipole or optical gradient force on the dielectric sphere.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The technique of using a focused laser beam as an atom trap was first applied in 1984 at Bell laboratories.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Until then experiments had been carried out using oppositely directed lasers as a means to trap particles.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Later experiments, at the same project at Bell laboratories and others since, showed damage-free manipulation on cells using an infrared laser.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Thus, the ground was made for biological experiments with optical trapping.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Each technique has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] For example, AFM cantilevers, can measure angstrom-scale, millisecond events and forces larger than 10 pN.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] While glass microfibers cannot achieve such fine spatial and temporal resolution, they can measure piconewton forces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Optical tweezers allow the measurement of piconewton forces and nanometer displacements which is an ideal range for many biological experiments.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Magnetic tweezers can measure femtonewton forces, and additionally they can also be used to apply torsion.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] AFS devices allow the statistical analysis of the mechanical properties of biological systems by applying picoNewton forces to hundreds of individual particles in parallel, with sub-millisecond response time.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Common applications of force spectroscopy are measurements of polymer elasticity, especially biopolymers such as RNA and DNA.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Another biophysical application of polymer force spectroscopy is on protein unfolding.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Modular proteins can be adsorbed to a gold or (more rarely) mica surface and then stretched.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The sequential unfolding of modules is observed as a very characteristic sawtooth pattern of the force vs elongation graph; every tooth corresponds to the unfolding of a single protein module (apart from the last that is generally the detachment of the protein molecule from the tip).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Much information about protein elasticity and protein unfolding can be obtained by this technique.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Many proteins in the living cell must face mechanical stress.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Moreover, force spectroscopy can be used to investigate the enzymatic activity of proteins involved in DNA replication, transcription, organization and repair.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] This is achieved by measuring the position of a bead attached to a DNA-protein complex stalled on a DNA tether that has one end attached to a surface, while keeping the force constant.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] This technique has been used, for example, to study transcription elongation inhibition by Klebsidin and Acinetodin.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The other main application of force spectroscopy is the study of mechanical resistance of chemical bonds.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In this case, generally the tip is functionalized with a ligand that binds to another molecule bound to the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The tip is pushed on the surface, allowing for contact between the two molecules, and then retracted until the newly formed bond breaks up.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] The force at which the bond breaks up is measured.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Since mechanical breaking is a kinetic, stochastic process, the breaking force is not an absolute parameter, but it is a function of both temperature and pulling speed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Low temperatures and high pulling speeds correspond to higher breaking forces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] By careful analysis of the breaking force at various pulling speeds, it is possible to map the energy landscape of the chemical bond under mechanical force.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] This is leading to interesting results in the study of antibody-antigen, protein-protein, protein-living cell interaction and catch bonds.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] Recently this technique has been used in cell biology to measure the aggregative stochastic forces created by motor proteins that influence the motion of particles within the cytoplasm.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/force-spectroscopy] In this way, force spectrum microscopy may be used better to understand the many cellular processes that require the motion of particles within cytoplasm.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect results from the linear electromechanical interaction between the mechanical and electrical states in crystalline materials with no inversion symmetry.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect is a reversible process: materials exhibiting the piezoelectric effect also exhibit the reverse piezoelectric effect, the internal generation of a mechanical strain resulting from an applied electric field.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For example, lead zirconate titanate crystals will generate measurable piezoelectricity when their static structure is deformed by about 0.1% of the original dimension.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Conversely, those same crystals will change about 0.1% of their static dimension when an external electric field is applied.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The inverse piezoelectric effect is used in the production of ultrasound waves.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] French physicists Jacques and Pierre Curie discovered piezoelectricity in 1880.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] It forms the basis for scanning probe microscopes that resolve images at the scale of atoms.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] It is used in the pickups of some electronically amplified guitars and as triggers in most modern electronic drums.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect also finds everyday uses, such as generating sparks to ignite gas cooking and heating devices, torches, and cigarette lighters.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The word *piezoelectricity* means electricity resulting from pressure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] It is derived from Ancient Greek πιέζω*(*piézō*)* 'to squeeze or press' and ἤλεκτρον*(*ḗlektron*)* 'amber' (an ancient source of static electricity).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The German form of the word (*Piezoelektrizität*) was coined in 1881 by the German physicist Wilhelm Gottlieb Hankel; the English word was derived from German in 1883.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The pyroelectric effect, by which a material generates an electric potential in response to a temperature change, was studied by Carl Linnaeus and Franz Aepinus in the mid-18th century.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Drawing on this knowledge, both René Just Haüy and Antoine César Becquerel posited a relationship between mechanical stress and electric charge; however, experiments by both proved inconclusive.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The first demonstration of the direct piezoelectric effect was in 1880 by the brothers Pierre Curie and Jacques Curie.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Quartz and Rochelle salt exhibited the most piezoelectricity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The Curies, however, did not predict the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The converse effect was mathematically deduced from fundamental thermodynamic principles by Gabriel Lippmann in 1881.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The Curies immediately confirmed the existence of the converse effect, and went on to obtain quantitative proof of the complete reversibility of electro-elasto-mechanical deformations in piezoelectric crystals.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For the next few decades, piezoelectricity remained something of a laboratory curiosity, though it was a vital tool in the discovery of polonium and radium by Pierre and Marie Curie in 1898.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] More work was done to explore and define the crystal structures that exhibited piezoelectricity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This culminated in 1910 with the publication of Woldemar Voigt's *Lehrbuch der Kristallphysik* (*Textbook on Crystal Physics*), which described the 20 natural crystal classes capable of piezoelectricity, and rigorously defined the piezoelectric constants using tensor analysis.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The first practical application for piezoelectric devices was sonar, first developed during World War I.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The superior performance of piezoelectric devices, operating at ultrasonic frequencies, superseded the earlier Fessenden oscillator.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In France in 1917, Paul Langevin and his coworkers developed an ultrasonic submarine detector.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The detector consisted of a transducer, made of thin quartz crystals carefully glued between two steel plates, and a hydrophone to detect the returned echo.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] By emitting a high-frequency pulse from the transducer, and measuring the amount of time it takes to hear an echo from the sound waves bouncing off an object, one can calculate the distance to that object.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric devices found homes in many fields.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ceramic phonograph cartridges simplified player design, were cheap and accurate, and made record players cheaper to maintain and easier to build.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The development of the ultrasonic transducer allowed for easy measurement of viscosity and elasticity in fluids and solids, resulting in huge advances in materials research.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic time-domain reflectometers (which send an ultrasonic pulse through a material and measure reflections from discontinuities) could find flaws inside cast metal and stone objects, improving structural safety.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] During World War II, independent research groups in the United States, USSR, and Japan discovered a new class of synthetic materials, called ferroelectrics, which exhibited piezoelectric constants many times higher than natural materials.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This led to intense research to develop barium titanate and later lead zirconate titanate materials with specific properties for particular applications.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] One significant example of the use of piezoelectric crystals was developed by Bell Telephone Laboratories.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Lack, working in radio telephony in the engineering department, developed the "AT cut" crystal, a crystal that operated through a wide range of temperatures.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Lack's crystal did not need the heavy accessories previous crystal used, facilitating its use on the aircraft.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This development allowed Allied air forces to engage in coordinated mass attacks through the use of aviation radio.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Development of piezoelectric devices and materials in the United States was kept within the companies doing the development, mostly due to the wartime beginnings of the field, and in the interests of securing profitable patents.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] New materials were the first to be developed—quartz crystals were the first commercially exploited piezoelectric material, but scientists searched for higher-performance materials.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Despite the advances in materials and the maturation of manufacturing processes, the United States market did not grow as quickly as Japan's did.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Without many new applications, the growth of the United States' piezoelectric industry suffered.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In contrast, Japanese manufacturers shared their information, quickly overcoming technical and manufacturing challenges and creating new markets.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In Japan, a temperature stable crystal cut was developed by Issac Koga.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Japanese efforts in materials research created piezoceramic materials competitive to the United States materials but free of expensive patent restrictions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers that transmit sound waves through air had existed for quite some time but first saw major commercial use in early television remote controls.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] These transducers now are mounted on several car models as an echolocation device, helping the driver determine the distance from the car to any objects that may be in its path.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The nature of the piezoelectric effect is closely related to the occurrence of electric dipole moments in solids.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] These may be either induced for ions on crystal lattice sites with asymmetric charge surroundings (as in BaTiO3 and PZTs) or directly carried by molecular groups (as in cane sugar).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The dipole density or polarization (dimensionality [C·m/m3] ) may easily be calculated for crystals by summing up the dipole moments per volume of the crystallographic unit cell.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] As every dipole is a vector, the dipole density ***P*** is a vector field.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Dipoles near each other tend to be aligned in regions called Weiss domains.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The domains are usually randomly oriented, but can be aligned using the process of *poling* (not the same as magnetic poling), a process by which a strong electric field is applied across the material, usually at elevated temperatures.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Not all piezoelectric materials can be poled.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Of importance for the piezoelectric effect is the change of polarization ***P*** when applying a mechanical stress.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This might either be caused by a reconfiguration of the dipole-inducing surrounding or by re-orientation of molecular dipole moments under the influence of the external stress.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectricity may then manifest in a variation of the polarization strength, its direction or both, with the details depending on: 1. the orientation of ***P*** within the crystal; 2. crystal symmetry; and 3. the applied mechanical stress.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The change in ***P*** appears as a variation of surface charge density upon the crystal faces, i.e. as a variation of the electric field extending between the faces caused by a change in dipole density in the bulk.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For example, a 1 cm3 cube of quartz with 2 kN (500 lbf) of correctly applied force can produce a voltage of 12500 V.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric materials also show the opposite effect, called the **converse piezoelectric effect**, where the application of an electrical field creates mechanical deformation in the crystal.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] where ${\mathfrak {d}}$ is the piezoelectric tensor and the superscript t stands for its transpose.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] where [*d*] is the matrix for the direct piezoelectric effect and [*d*t] is the matrix for the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The superscript *E* indicates a zero, or constant, electric field; the superscript *T* indicates a zero, or constant, stress field; and the superscript t stands for transposition of a matrix.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Notice that the third order tensor ${\mathfrak {d}}$ maps vectors into symmetric matrices.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] There are no non-trivial rotation-invariant tensors that have this property, which is why there are no isotropic piezoelectric materials.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] where the first equation represents the relationship for the converse piezoelectric effect and the latter for the direct piezoelectric effect.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Although the above equations are the most used form in literature, some comments about the notation are necessary.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Generally, *D* and *E* are vectors, that is, Cartesian tensors of rank 1; and permittivity *ε* is a Cartesian tensor of rank 2.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Strain and stress are, in principle, also rank-2 tensors.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] But conventionally, because strain and stress are all symmetric tensors, the subscript of strain and stress can be relabeled in the following fashion: 11 → 1; 22 → 2; 33 → 3; 23 → 4; 13 → 5; 12 → 6.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] (Different conventions may be used by different authors in literature.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For example, some use 12 → 4; 23 → 5; 31 → 6 instead.) That is why *S* and *T* appear to have the "vector form" of six components.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Consequently, *s* appears to be a 6-by-6 matrix instead of a rank-3 tensor.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Such a relabeled notation is often called Voigt notation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Whether the shear strain components *S*4, *S*5, *S*6 are tensor components or engineering strains is another question.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In the equation above, they must be engineering strains for the 6,6 coefficient of the compliance matrix to be written as shown, i.e., 2(*s**E* 11 − *s**E* 12).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Engineering shear strains are double the value of the corresponding tensor shear, such as *S*6 = 2*S*12 and so on.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This also means that *s*66 = ⁠1/*G*12⁠, where *G*12 is the shear modulus.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] where the first set of four terms corresponds to the direct piezoelectric effect and the second set of four terms corresponds to the converse piezoelectric effect.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The equality between the direct piezoelectric tensor and the transpose of the converse piezoelectric tensor originates from the Maxwell relations of thermodynamics.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For those piezoelectric crystals for which the polarization is of the crystal-field induced type, a formalism has been worked out that allows for the calculation of piezoelectrical coefficients *dij* from electrostatic lattice constants or higher-order Madelung constants.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Of the 32 crystal classes, 21 are non-centrosymmetric (not having a centre of symmetry), and of these, 20 exhibit direct piezoelectricity (the 21st is the cubic class 432).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ten of these represent the polar crystal classes, which show a spontaneous polarization without mechanical stress due to a non-vanishing electric dipole moment associated with their unit cell, and which exhibit pyroelectricity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] If the dipole moment can be reversed by applying an external electric field, the material is said to be ferroelectric.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For polar crystals, for which ***P*** ≠ 0 holds without applying a mechanical load, the piezoelectric effect manifests itself by changing the magnitude or the direction of ***P*** or both.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For the nonpolar but piezoelectric crystals, on the other hand, a polarization ***P*** different from zero is only elicited by applying a mechanical load.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For them the stress can be imagined to transform the material from a nonpolar crystal class (***P*** = 0) to a polar one, having ***P*** ≠ 0.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Many materials exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ceramics with randomly oriented grains must be ferroelectric to exhibit piezoelectricity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Macroscopic piezoelectricity is possible in textured polycrystalline non-ferroelectric piezoelectric materials, such as AlN and ZnO.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The fabrication of lead-free piezoceramics pose multiple challenges, from an environmental standpoint and their ability to replicate the properties of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] By removing the lead component of the piezoceramic, the risk of toxicity to humans decreases, but the mining and extraction of the materials can be harmful to the environment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Most of the concerns with KNN, specifically its Nb2O5 component, are in the early phase of its life cycle before it reaches manufacturers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Since the harmful impacts are focused on these early phases, some actions can be taken to minimize the effects.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Returning the land as close to its original form after Nb2O5 mining via dam deconstruction or replacing a stockpile of utilizable soil are known aids for any extraction event.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For minimizing air quality effects, modeling and simulation still needs to occur to fully understand what mitigation methods are required.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The extraction of lead-free piezoceramic components has not grown to a significant scale at this time, but from early analysis, experts encourage caution when it comes to environmental effects.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Fabricating lead-free piezoceramics faces the challenge of maintaining the performance and stability of their lead-based counterparts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In general, the main fabrication challenge is creating the "morphotropic phase boundaries (MPBs)" that provide the materials with their stable piezoelectric properties without introducing the "polymorphic phase boundaries (PPBs)" that decrease the temperature stability of the material.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] New phase boundaries are created by varying additive concentrations so that the phase transition temperatures converge at room temperature.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The introduction of the MPB improves piezoelectric properties, but if a PPB is introduced, the material becomes negatively affected by temperature.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Research is ongoing to control the type of phase boundaries that are introduced through phase engineering, diffusing phase transitions, domain engineering, and chemical modification.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] A piezoelectric potential can be created in any bulk or nanostructured semiconductor crystal having non central symmetry, such as the Group III–V and II–VI materials, due to polarization of ions under applied stress and strain.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] This property is common to both the zincblende and wurtzite crystal structures.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] To first order, there is only one independent piezoelectric coefficient in zincblende, called e14, coupled to shear components of the strain.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In wurtzite, there are instead three independent piezoelectric coefficients: *e*31, *e*33 and *e*15.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The semiconductors where the strongest piezoelectricity is observed are those commonly found in the wurtzite structure, i.e.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] GaN, InN, AlN and ZnO (see piezotronics).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Since 2006, there have also been a number of reports of strong non linear piezoelectric effects in polar semiconductors.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Such effects are generally recognized to be at least important if not of the same order of magnitude as the first order approximation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response of polymers is not as high as the response for ceramics; however, polymers hold properties that ceramics do not.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Over the last few decades, non-toxic, piezoelectric polymers have been studied and applied due to their flexibility and smaller acoustical impedance.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Other properties that make these materials significant include their biocompatibility, biodegradability, low cost, and low power consumption compared to other piezo-materials (ceramics, etc.).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric polymers can be classified by bulk polymers, voided charged polymers ("piezoelectrets"), and polymer composites.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] A piezo-response observed by bulk polymers is mostly due to its molecular structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] There are two types of bulk polymers: amorphous and semi-crystalline.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Examples of semi-crystalline polymers are polyvinylidene fluoride (PVDF) and its copolymers, polyamides, and parylene-C.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Non-crystalline polymers, such as polyimide and polyvinylidene chloride (PVDC), fall under amorphous bulk polymers.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Voided charged polymers exhibit the piezoelectric effect due to charge induced by poling of a porous polymeric film.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Under an electric field, charges form on the surface of the voids forming dipoles.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Electric responses can be caused by any deformation of these voids.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectric effect can also be observed in polymer composites by integrating piezoelectric ceramic particles into a polymer film.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] A polymer does not have to be piezo-active to be an effective material for a polymer composite.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In this case, a material could be made up of an inert matrix with a separate piezo-active component.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] PVDF exhibits piezoelectricity several times greater than quartz.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezo-response observed from PVDF is about 20–30 pC/N.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] That is an order of 5–50 times less than that of piezoelectric ceramic lead zirconate titanate (PZT).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The thermal stability of the piezoelectric effect of polymers in the PVDF family (i.e. vinylidene fluoride co-poly trifluoroethylene) goes up to 125 °C.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Some applications of PVDF are pressure sensors, hydrophones, and shock wave sensors.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Due to their flexibility, piezoelectric composites have been proposed as energy harvesters and nanogenerators.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In 2018, it was reported by Zhu et al. that a piezoelectric response of about 17 pC/N could be obtained from PDMS/PZT nanocomposite at 60% porosity.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Another PDMS nanocomposite was reported in 2017, in which BaTiO3 was integrated into PDMS to make a stretchable, transparent nanogenerator for self-powered physiological monitoring.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In 2016, polar molecules were introduced into a polyurethane foam in which high responses of up to 244 pC/N were reported.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Most materials exhibit at least weak piezoelectric responses.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Trivial examples include sucrose (table sugar), DNA, and viral proteins, including those from bacteriophage.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] An actuator based on wood fibers (cellulose fibers) has been reported.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] D33 responses for cellular polypropylene are around 200 pC/N.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Some applications of cellular polypropylene are musical key pads, microphones, and ultrasound-based echolocation systems.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Recently, a single amino acid, β-glycine, displayed a high piezoelectric response of 178 pm V−1 compared with other biological materials.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ionic liquids were recently identified as the first piezoelectric liquid.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Direct piezoelectricity of some substances, like quartz, can generate potential differences of thousands of volts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The principle of operation of a piezoelectric sensor is that a physical dimension, transformed into a force, acts on two opposing faces of the sensing element.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Depending on the design of a sensor, different "modes" to load the piezoelectric element can be used: longitudinal, transversal and shear.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Detection of pressure variations in the form of sound is the most common sensor application, e.g. piezoelectric microphones (sound waves bend the piezoelectric material, creating a changing voltage) and piezoelectric pickups for acoustic-electric guitars.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] A piezo sensor attached to the body of an instrument is known as a contact microphone.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric sensors especially are used with high frequency sound in ultrasonic transducers for medical imaging and also industrial nondestructive testing (NDT).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For many sensing techniques, the sensor can act as both a sensor and an actuator—often the term *transducer* is preferred when the device acts in this dual capacity, but most piezo devices have this property of reversibility whether it is used or not.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Ultrasonic transducers, for example, can inject ultrasound waves into the body, receive the returned wave, and convert it to an electrical signal (a voltage).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Most medical ultrasound transducers are piezoelectric.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] As very high electric fields correspond to only tiny changes in the width of the crystal, this width can be changed with better-than-μm precision, making piezo crystals the most important tool for positioning objects with extreme accuracy—thus their use in actuators.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Multilayer ceramics, using layers thinner than 100 μm, allow reaching high electric fields with voltage lower than 150 V.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] These ceramics are used within two kinds of actuators: direct piezo actuators and amplified piezoelectric actuators.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] While direct actuator's stroke is generally lower than 100 μm, amplified piezo actuators can reach millimeter strokes.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The piezoelectrical properties of quartz are useful as a standard of frequency.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Aside from the stepping stick-slip motor, all these motors work on the same principle.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Driven by dual orthogonal vibration modes with a phase difference of 90°, the contact point between two surfaces vibrates in an elliptical path, producing a frictional force between the surfaces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Usually, one surface is fixed, causing the other to move.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In most piezoelectric motors, the piezoelectric crystal is excited by a sine wave signal at the resonant frequency of the motor.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Using the resonance effect, a much lower voltage can be used to produce a high vibration amplitude.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] A stick-slip motor works using the inertia of a mass and the friction of a clamp.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Some are used for camera sensor displacement, thus allowing an anti-shake function.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Different teams of researchers have been investigating ways to reduce vibrations in materials by attaching piezo elements to the material.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] When the material is bent by a vibration in one direction, the vibration-reduction system responds to the bend and sends electric power to the piezo element to bend in the other direction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Applications to flexible structures, such as shells and plates, have also been studied for nearly three decades.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezosurgery is a minimally invasive technique that aims to cut a target tissue with little damage to neighboring tissues.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] For example, Hoigne *et al.* uses frequencies in the range 25–29 kHz, causing microvibrations of 60–210 μm.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] It has the ability to cut mineralized tissue without cutting neurovascular tissue and other soft tissue, thereby maintaining a blood-free operating area, better visibility and greater precision.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] In 2019, Pernas-Salomón and Shmuel developed a dynamic homogenization method by which they were the first to show that piezoelectric composites exhibit an effective coupling between linear momentum and the electric field, which they termed electro-momentum coupling.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Because homogeneous piezoelectric materials do not exhibit this coupling, such composites belong to the class of metamaterials—artificial media engineered to display extraordinary effective properties, in magnitude or in kind.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Electro-momentum coupling is analogous to Willis coupling in elastic composites, which couples linear momentum to strain and was discovered by J.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] The local part of these couplings—like piezoelectric coupling—emerges from broken symmetries.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/piezoelectricity] Piezoelectric metamaterials with electro-momentum coupling offer a mechanism for wave manipulation akin to Willis coupling: they impart a direction-dependent phase shift that enables wavefront shaping, with the added advantage of electrical tunability.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Many scanning probe microscopes can image several interactions simultaneously.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The manner of using these interactions to obtain an image is generally called a mode.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The resolution varies somewhat from technique to technique, but some probe techniques reach a rather impressive atomic resolution.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This is largely because piezoelectric actuators can execute motions with a precision and accuracy at the atomic level or better on electronic command.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This family of techniques can be called "piezoelectric techniques".
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The other common denominator is that the data are typically obtained as a two-dimensional grid of data points, visualized in false color as a computer image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] To form images, scanning probe microscopes raster scan the tip over the surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] At discrete points in the raster scan a value is recorded (which value depends on the type of SPM and the mode of operation, see below).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] These recorded values are displayed as a heat map to produce the final STM images, usually using a black and white or an orange color scale.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] In constant interaction mode (often referred to as "in feedback"), a feedback loop is used to physically move the probe closer to or further from the surface (in the *z* axis) under study to maintain a constant interaction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This interaction depends on the type of SPM, for scanning tunneling microscopy the interaction is the tunnel current, for contact mode AFM or MFM it is the cantilever deflection, etc.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The type of feedback loop used is usually a PI-loop, which is a PID-loop where the differential gain has been set to zero (as it amplifies noise).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The *z* position of the tip (scanning plane is the *xy*-plane) is recorded periodically and displayed as a heat map.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This is normally referred to as a topography image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] In this mode a second image, known as the ″error signal" or "error image" is also taken, which is a heat map of the interaction which was fed back on.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Under perfect operation this image would be a blank at a constant value which was set on the feedback loop.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Under real operation the image shows noise and often some indication of the surface structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The user can use this image to edit the feedback gains to minimise features in the error signal.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] If the gains are set incorrectly, many imaging artifacts are possible.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] If gains are too low features can appear smeared.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] If the gains are too high the feedback can become unstable and oscillate, producing striped features in the images which are not physical.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] In constant height mode the probe is not moved in the *z*-axis during the raster scan.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Instead the value of the interaction under study is recorded (i.e. the tunnel current for STM, or the cantilever oscillation amplitude for amplitude modulated non-contact AFM).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This recorded information is displayed as a heat map, and is usually referred to as a constant height image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Constant height imaging is much more difficult than constant interaction imaging as the probe is much more likely to crash into the sample surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Usually before performing constant height imaging one must image in constant interaction mode to check the surface has no large contaminants in the imaging region, to measure and correct for the sample tilt, and (especially for slow scans) to measure and correct for thermal drift of the sample.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Piezoelectric creep can also be a problem, so the microscope often needs time to settle after large movements before constant height imaging can be performed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Constant height imaging can be advantageous for eliminating the possibility of feedback artifacts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The nature of an SPM probe tip depends entirely on the type of SPM being used.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The combination of tip shape and topography of the sample make up a SPM image.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] However, certain characteristics are common to all, or at least most, SPMs.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Most importantly the probe must have a very sharp apex.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The apex of the probe defines the resolution of the microscope, the sharper the probe the better the resolution.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] For atomic resolution imaging the probe must be terminated by a single atom.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] AFM and MFM), the entire cantilever and integrated probe are fabricated by acid [etching], usually from silicon nitride.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Conducting probes, needed for STM and SCM among others, are usually constructed from platinum/iridium wire for ambient operations, or tungsten for UHV operation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Other materials such as gold are sometimes used either for sample specific reasons or if the SPM is to be combined with other experiments such as TERS.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Platinum/iridium (and other ambient) probes are normally cut using sharp wire cutters, the optimal method is to cut most of the way through the wire and then pull to snap the last of the wire, increasing the likelihood of a single atom termination.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Tungsten wires are usually electrochemically etched, following this the oxide layer normally needs to be removed once the tip is in UHV conditions.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] It is not uncommon for SPM probes (both purchased and "home-made") to not image with the desired resolution.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This may occur if the tip is too blunt or if the probe has more than one apex, which can lead to doubled or ghost images.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] For some probes, *in situ* modification of the tip apex is possible, this is usually done by either crashing the tip into the surface or by applying a large electric field.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The latter is achieved by applying a bias voltage (of order 10V) between the tip and the sample, as this distance is usually 1-3 Angstroms, a very large field is generated.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The resolution of these microscopes is not limited by diffraction but rather by the size of the probe-sample interaction volume (i.e., point spread function), which can be as small as a few picometres.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Hence the ability to measure small local differences in object height (like that of 135 picometre steps on <100> silicon) is unparalleled.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Laterally the probe-sample interaction extends only across the tip atom or atoms involved in the interaction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The interaction can be used to modify the sample to create small structures (Scanning probe lithography).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Unlike electron microscope methods, specimens do not require a partial vacuum but can be observed in air at standard temperature and pressure or while submerged in a liquid reaction vessel.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The detailed shape of the scanning tip is sometimes difficult to determine.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Its effect on the resulting data is particularly noticeable if the specimen varies greatly in height over lateral distances of 10 nm or less.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The scanning techniques are generally slower in acquiring images, due to the scanning process.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] As a result, efforts are being made to greatly improve the scanning rate.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Like all scanning techniques, the embedding of spatial information into a time sequence opens the door to uncertainties in metrology, such as in measuring lateral spacings and angles, which arise due to time-domain effects like specimen drift, feedback loop oscillations, and mechanical vibrations.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The maximum image size is generally smaller.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Scanning probe microscopy is often not useful for examining buried solid-solid or liquid-liquid interfaces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Scanning photo current microscopy can be considered as a member of the Scanning Probe Microscopy (SPM) family.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The difference between other SPM techniques and SPCM is, it exploits a focused laser beam as the local excitation source instead of a probe tip.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Characterization and analysis of spatially resolved optical behavior of materials is very important in opto-electronic industry.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Simply this involves studying how the properties of a material vary across its surface or bulk structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Techniques that enable spatially resolved optoelectronic measurements provide valuable insights for the enhancement of optical performance.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Scanning photo electron microscopy has emerged as a powerful technique which can investigate spatially resolved optoelectronic properties in semiconductor nano structures.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] In scanning photo current microscopy, a focused laser beam is used to excite the semiconducting material producing excitons (electro-hole pairs).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] These excitons undergo different mechanisms and if they can reach the nearby electrodes before the recombination takes place a photocurrent is generated.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] This photocurrent is position dependent as it, raster scans the device.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Using the position dependent photocurrent map, important photocurrent dynamics can be analyzed.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Scanning photocurrent microscopy provides information on carrier transport, such as minority carrier diffusion length and recombination dynamics, as well as on local doping concentration and built-in electric fields.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] In all instances and contrary to optical microscopes, rendering software is necessary to produce images.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] Such software is produced and embedded by instrument manufacturers but also available as an accessory from specialized work groups or companies.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/scanning-probe-microscopy] The main packages used are freeware: Gwyddion, WSxM (developed by Nanotec) and commercial: SPIP (developed by Image Metrology), FemtoScan Online (developed by Advanced Technologies Center), MountainsMap SPM (developed by Digital Surf), TopoStitch (developed by Image Metrology).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] In surface metrology, surface roughness is a component of surface finish (surface texture).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] It is quantified by the deviations in the direction of the normal vector of a real surface from its ideal form.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] If these deviations are large, the surface is rough; if they are small, the surface is smooth.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Roughness is typically assumed to be the high-frequency, short-wavelength component of a measured surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] However, in practice it is often necessary to know both the amplitude and frequency to ensure that a surface is fit for a purpose.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Roughness plays an important role in determining how a real object will interact with its environment.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] In tribology, rough surfaces usually wear more quickly and have higher friction coefficients than smooth surfaces.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Roughness is often a good predictor of the performance of a mechanical component, since irregularities on the surface may form nucleation sites for cracks or corrosion.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] On the other hand, roughness may promote adhesion.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Generally speaking, rather than scale specific descriptors, cross-scale descriptors such as surface fractality provide more meaningful predictions of mechanical interactions at surfaces including contact stiffness and static friction.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Although a high roughness value is often undesirable, it can be difficult and expensive to control in manufacturing.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, it is difficult and expensive to control surface roughness of fused deposition modelling (FDM) manufactured parts.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Decreasing the roughness of a surface usually increases its manufacturing cost.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] This often results in a trade-off between the manufacturing cost of a component and its performance in application.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Roughness can be measured by manual comparison against a "surface roughness comparator" (a sample of known surface roughness), but more generally a surface profile measurement is made with a profilometer.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] These can be of the contact variety (typically a diamond stylus) or optical (e.g.: a white light interferometer or laser scanning confocal microscope).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] However, controlled roughness can often be desirable.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, a gloss surface can be too shiny to the eye and too slippery to the finger (a touchpad is a good example) so a controlled roughness is required.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] This is a case where both amplitude and frequency are very important.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Surface structure plays a key role in governing contact mechanics, that is to say the mechanical behavior exhibited at an interface between two solid objects as they approach each other and transition from conditions of non-contact to full contact.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] In particular, normal contact stiffness is governed predominantly by asperity structures (roughness, surface slope and fractality) and material properties.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] In terms of engineering surfaces, roughness is considered to be detrimental to part performance.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] As a consequence, most manufacturing prints establish an upper limit on roughness, but not a lower limit.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] An exception is in cylinder bores where oil is retained in the surface profile and a minimum roughness is required.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Surface structure is often closely related to the friction and wear properties of a surface.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] A surface with a higher fractal dimension, large $Ra$ value, or a positive $Rsk$ , will usually have somewhat higher friction and wear quickly.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The peaks in the roughness profile are not always the points of contact.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The form and waviness (i.e. both amplitude and frequency) must also be considered.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] A roughness value can either be calculated on a profile (line) or on a surface (area).
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The profile roughness parameter ( $Ra$ , $Rq$ , ...) are more common.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The area roughness parameters ( $Sa$ , $Sq$ , ...) give more significant values.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The profile roughness parameters are included in BS EN ISO 4287:2000 British standard, identical with the ISO 4287:1997 standard.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The standard is based on the ″M″ (mean line) system.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] There are many different roughness parameters in use, but $Ra$ is by far the most common, though this is often for historical reasons and not for particular merit, as the early roughness meters could only measure $Ra$ .
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Other common parameters include $Rz$ , $Rq$ , and $Rsk$ .
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Some parameters are used only in certain industries or within certain countries.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, the $Rk$ family of parameters is used mainly for cylinder bore linings, and the *Motif parameters* are used primarily in the French automotive industry.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The MOTIF method provides a graphical evaluation of a surface profile without filtering waviness from roughness.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] A *motif* consists of the portion of a profile between two peaks and the final combinations of these motifs eliminate ″insignificant″ peaks and retains ″significant″ ones.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Please note that $Ra$ is a dimensional unit that can be micrometer or microinch.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Since these parameters reduce all of the information in a profile to a single number, great care must be taken in applying and interpreting them.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Small changes in how the raw profile data is filtered, how the mean line is calculated, and the physics of the measurement can greatly affect the calculated parameter.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] With modern digital equipment, the scan can be evaluated to make sure there are no obvious glitches that skew the values.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Because it may not be obvious to many users what each of the measurements really mean, a simulation tool allows a user to adjust key parameters, visualizing how surfaces which are obviously different to the human eye are differentiated by the measurements.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, $Ra$ fails to distinguish between two surfaces where one is composed of peaks on an otherwise smooth surface and the other is composed of troughs of the same amplitude.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] By convention every 2D roughness parameter is a capital R followed by additional characters in the subscript.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The subscript identifies the formula that was used, and the R means that the formula was applied to a 2D roughness profile.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Different capital letters imply that the formula was applied to a different profile.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, $Ra$ is the arithmetic average of the roughness profile, $Pa$ is the arithmetic average of the unfiltered raw profile, and $Sa$ is the arithmetic average of the 3D roughness.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Each of the formulas listed in the tables assumes that the roughness profile has been filtered from the raw profile data and the mean line has been calculated.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The roughness profile contains n ordered, equally spaced points along the trace, and $y_{i}$ is the vertical distance from the mean line to the $i^{\text{th}}$ data point.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Height is assumed to be positive in the up direction, away from the bulk material.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Amplitude parameters characterize the surface based on the vertical deviations of the roughness profile from the mean line.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Many of them are closely related to the parameters found in statistics for characterizing population samples.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For example, $Ra$ is the arithmetic average value of filtered roughness profile determined from deviations about the center line within the evaluation length and $Rt$ is the range of the collected roughness data points.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The arithmetic average roughness, $Ra$ , is the most widely used one-dimensional roughness parameter.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Slope parameters describe characteristics of the slope of the roughness profile.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Spacing and counting parameters describe how often the profile crosses certain thresholds.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] These parameters are often used to describe repetitive roughness profiles, such as those produced by turning on a lathe.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Other "frequency" parameters are Sm, $\lambda$ a and $\lambda$ q.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Just as with real mountains it is important to define a "peak".
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] For Sm the surface must have dipped below the mean surface before rising again to a new peak.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The average wavelength $\lambda$ a and the root mean square wavelength $\lambda$ q are derived from $\Delta$ a.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] When trying to understand a surface that depends on both amplitude and frequency it is not obvious which pair of metrics optimally describes the balance, so a statistical analysis of pairs of measurements can be performed (e.g.: Rz and $\lambda$ a or Ra and Sm) to find the strongest correlation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] These parameters are based on the bearing ratio curve (also known as the Abbott-Firestone curve.) This includes the Rk family of parameters.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The mathematician Benoît Mandelbrot has pointed out the connection between surface roughness and fractal dimension.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] The description provided by a fractal at the microroughness level may allow the control of the material properties and the type of the occurring chip formation.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] But fractals cannot provide a full-scale representation of a typical machined surface affected by tool feed marks; it ignores the geometry of the cutting edge.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Fractal descriptors of surfaces have an important role to play in correlating physical surface properties with surface structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Across multiple fields, connecting physical, electrical and mechanical behavior with conventional surface descriptors of roughness or slope has been challenging.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] By employing measures of surface fractality together with measures of roughness or surface shape, certain interfacial phenomena including contact mechanics, friction and electrical contact resistance, can be better interpreted with respect to surface structure.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Areal roughness parameters are defined in the ISO 25178 series.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Many optical measurement instruments are able to measure the surface roughness over an area.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Area measurements are also possible with contact measurement systems.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] Multiple, closely spaced 2D scans are taken of the target area.
[src:atomic-force-microscopy/surface-roughness] These are then digitally stitched together using relevant software, resulting in a 3D image and accompanying areal roughness parameters.
